'''Hungarian comics''' are [[comics]] made in [[Hungary]] and by the [[Hungary#Ethnic Hungarians in neighbouring countries | Hungarian diaspora of the surrounding countries]]. When dealing with Hungarian comics, one cannot separate comics made by Hungarians from translated foreign matter, since in some eras most of the publications come from the latter group and influence comics fandom and the general picture about comics in the country.

==Vocabulary==
The Hungarian word for comics is ''k<U+00E9>preg<U+00E9>ny'', a combined word from ''k<U+00E9>p'' (picture) and ''reg<U+00E9>ny'' (novel). The words ''comics'' (referring to [[American comics]]), ''[[manga]]'' (referring to mainly Japanese comics), ''bd / bande dessin<U+00E9>e'' (referring to [[Franco-Belgian comics]]) are sometimes used in Hungarian context, but are not general except for the case of manga.

==History <ref>The History section of the article (until 1989) is based on the following books and articles:<br>
S<U+00E1>ndor Kert<U+00E9>sz: Szuperh<U+0151>s<U+00F6>k Magyarorsz<U+00E1>gon, Akvarell Bt., 1991<br>
S<U+00E1>ndor Kert<U+00E9>sz: Comics szocialista <U+00E1>lruh<U+00E1>ban, Kert<U+00E9>sz Nyomda <U+00E9>s Kiad<U+00F3>, 2007<br>
Ferenc Kiss: A k<U+00E9>preg<U+00E9>ny sz<U+00FC>let<U+00E9>se <U+00E9>s hal<U+00E1>la Magyarorsz<U+00E1>gon in Besz<U+00E9>l<U+0151> 2005/1<br>
[http://www.kepregeny.net/?page_id=1557 Ferenc Kiss & Zolt<U+00E1>n <U+00C1>d<U+00E1>m Szab<U+00F3>: Melyik a t<U+00F6>bbi nyolc? in Besz<U+00E9>l<U+0151> 2005/12]</ref>==
(The history of Hungarian comics is best divided along political eras, because of the great influence politics made on comics.)

===From the 19th century until World War I===
[[Image:Janko Hazank.jpg|thumb|right|A J<U+00E1>nos Jank<U+00F3> sequentally illustrated story in a Hungarian news journal, 1867.]]During the late 19th century Hungary, as part of the [[Austria-Hungary | Austro-Hungarian Empire]], kept pace with the European trends, pointing in the direction of what later became to be known as modern comics. [[Rodolphe T<U+00F6>pffer]] and [[Wilhelm Busch]] (Max und Moritz) had great effect on Hungarian journalism, and soon the Hungarian equivalents were born. One of the most important writers of the time, [[M<U+00F3>r J<U+00F3>kai]] founded (1858 August 21) and edited a magazine called ''<U+00DC>st<U+00F6>k<U+00F6>s'' (comet) based on the [[Fliegende Bl<U+00E4>tter]]. Pages were filled with [[caricature|caricatures]] and "''pictorial stories''" (k<U+00E9>pt<U+00F6>rt<U+00E9>netek, k<U+00E9>pes t<U+00F6>rt<U+00E9>netek), the European predecessor of modern comics. A short story was told in few sequential pictures, and the text (many times in rhyming poetic form) was placed beneath the images. Many similar journals existed besides <U+00DC>st<U+00F6>k<U+00F6>s. Hungary had a flourishing caricature culture at the time, and many of the greatest artists also drew these early types of comics.
====Most notable artists of the era====
*J<U+00E1>nos Jank<U+00F3>
*K<U+00E1>roly M<U+00FC>hlbeck, who created a unique form of the comic strip, that headlined newspapers.
*<U+00C1>kos Garay
*Milti<U+00E1>desz Mann<U+00F3>
*Antal G<U+00E1>sp<U+00E1>r
*Lajos Linek

===Between the two wars===
[[Image:Harijanos-01.jpg|thumb|right|First issue of H<U+00E1>ri J<U+00E1>nos, with a page of [[Lyman Young]]'s [[Tim Tyler's Luck]] translated as Pusk<U+00E1>s Pista]]The comic strip boom of the USA had a growing effect on Hungarian newspaper publishing until the late thirties. American comics flooded all kinds of newspapers, magazines. ''H<U+00E1>ri J<U+00E1>nos'' (see image) (1936-1937<ref>[http://www.karton.hu/cgi-bin/index.php?p=8&m=12 Gergely Nagy: A hazai k<U+00E9>preg<U+00E9>nyr<U+0151>l (About Hungarian comics). kArton galery homepage, 2003.01.01]</ref>), a magazine for children is considered to be the first Hugnarian comic book magazine, with comic strips on every page. [[Disney comics|Walt Disney strips]], Secret Agent X-09, [[Little Nemo in Slumberland]] (Kis N<U+00E9>m<U+00F3> <U+00C1>lomorsz<U+00E1>gban), [[George McManus]] strips and many others marked this period.
Not as many Hungarian comics were made in this period, while <U+2013> for example <U+2013> Yugoslavia, the southern neighbor, claims this period to be their Golden Age.<ref>[http://www.rastko.org.yu/strip/zzupan-golden_age.html Zdravko Zupan: The Golden Age of Serbian Comics. Projekat Rastko, Spring-1999]</ref>

During this period the [[Treaty of Trianon|truncated Hungary]] was an ally of Germany. In 1937 the Minister of Justice began restricting the great amount of pulp literature and yellow press. In 1938 a decree ordered the whole press under the control of the Government. In the same year the "First Jewish Law" was issued.<ref>A brief summary of the law in English: [http://www.porges.net/JewishHistoryOfHungary.html#1919%20to%201939 Naftali Kraus: Jewish History of Hungary 1919 to 1939. Porges Families Homepage.]</ref> Among others the goal of these two were to <U+201C>clean<U+201D> Hungary<U+2019>s cultural life, to eliminate pulp literature. As the <U+00DA>js<U+00E1>g, a Hungarian extremist newspaper, commented in 1938: ''"These are not at all capable to nurture Hungarian self-knowledge, Hungarian honesty, Hungarian heroism, consequentially to nurture the Hungarian folk, national and racial self-knowledge."''<ref>"Ezek egy<U+00E1>ltal<U+00E1>n nem alkalmasak a magyar <U+00F6>nismeret, a magyar becs<U+00FC>let, a magyar h<U+0151>siess<U+00E9>g, teh<U+00E1>t a magyar n<U+00E9>pi, nemzeti <U+00E9>s faji <U+00F6>ntudat <U+00E1>pol<U+00E1>s<U+00E1>ra..."<br>original quote from <U+00DA>js<U+00E1>g 1938. April 22</ref> Since most of the comics were published in the mostly Jewish owned [[Yellow journalism | yellow press]], comics vanished after the law took effect. The situation became even worse after the German troops marched in Hungary: all leftist and liberal media was banned. The only comics of the time were antisemitic ones from magazines as the militant Harc ("''Combat''") or anticommunist ones from newspapers as Egyed<U+00FC>l vagyunk ("''We are alone''"). <ref name="szoci">S<U+00E1>ndor Kert<U+00E9>sz: Comics szocialista <U+00E1>lruh<U+00E1>ban, Kert<U+00E9>sz Nyomda <U+00E9>s Kiad<U+00F3>, 2007</ref> <ref name="melyik">[http://www.kepregeny.net/?page_id=1557 Ferenc Kiss & Zolt<U+00E1>n <U+00C1>d<U+00E1>m Szab<U+00F3>: Melyik a t<U+00F6>bbi nyolc? in Besz<U+00E9>l<U+0151> 2005/12 ]</ref>
====Notable artists of the era====
